Textbook Support for Implementation Decisions

  Here are the relevant chapters and sections from Manning, Raghavan & Schütze (2009),
  Introduction to Information Retrieval (Cambridge University Press), organized by
  implementation decision:

  ---
  1. Preprocessing Pipeline

  Tokenization (§2.2.1, p.22):
  "The first step of determining the index units is tokenization... We need to choose what
  constitutes a token."

  Justifies splitting text into tokens as the first indexing step.

  Stop Word Removal (§2.2.2, p.27–28):
  "Some extremely common words which would appear to be of little value in helping select
  documents matching a user need are excluded from the vocabulary entirely. These words are
   called stop words."
  "Using a stop list significantly reduces the number of postings that a system has to
  store."

  This justifies removing stop words from title and author fields (via preprocess_field()),
   while body queries retain stop words — matching how the body was indexed with stopwords
  present — to avoid zero-result queries like "to be, or not to be."

  Normalization (§2.2.3, p.28–31):
  "Token normalization is the process of canonicalizing tokens so that matches occur
  despite superficial differences in the character sequences of the tokens."
  "The most standard way to normalize is to implicitly create equivalence classes, which
  are normally named after one member of the set. A simple normalization form is to put
  words in lowercase."

  Justifies Unicode normalization and lowercasing.

  Stemming / Porter Algorithm (§2.2.4, p.32–35):
  "Stemming usually refers to a crude heuristic process that chops off the ends of words in
   the hope of achieving this goal correctly most of the time, and often includes the
  removal of derivational affixes."
  "The most common algorithm for stemming English... is Porter's algorithm (Porter, 1980)."

  Supports use of NLTK's Porter stemmer during preprocessing.

  ---
  2. Positional Index

  (§2.4.2, p.41–44):
  "In a positional index, for each term in the vocabulary, we store postings of the form
  docID: ⟨position1, position2, ...⟩, where each position is a token index in the
  document."
  "Positional indexes are substantially larger than a regular inverted index, but they
  allow phrase queries."

  Justifies storing position arrays (as binary array.array('I') blobs) in the body_index
  table for phrase matching.

  ---
  3. Index Construction

  (Chapter 4, p.67–85 — BSBI & SPIMI):
  "For large document collections, the index has to be constructed using an algorithm that
  works with limited main memory. Instead of loading all postings into memory at once, we
  build the index in a blocked, sorted fashion."

  Justifies the batch-insert approach (BATCH_SIZE=500) with SQLite WAL mode for building
  the index over 70,000+ documents without memory issues.

  ---
  4. Structured Search (TF Scoring with Field Weights)

  Weighted Zone Scoring (§6.1.1, p.112–115):
  "In weighted zone scoring, we assign a weight to each zone of the document... the score
  of a document d is: score(d,q) = Σ gᵢ × sᵢ(d,q) where gᵢ are the zone weights and sᵢ is
  the boolean score in zone i."
  "The weights gᵢ sum to 1 and are between 0 and 1."

  This directly justifies the field weights used: title=3.0, author=2.0, body=1.0
  (normalized internally when combining scores across fields).

  TF Weighting (§6.2, p.117–118):
  "A document with a term frequency of tf has more relevance signal than a document with tf
   = 1... The raw term frequency tf_{t,d} of term t in document d is the number of times t
  occurs in d."

  Justifies using raw TF normalized by document length (tf / doc_len) for structured
  scoring.

  ---
  5. Vector Space Model (VSM)

  TF–IDF and Vector Space Model (§6.3, p.120–126):
  "We now combine the notions of tf and idf... The tf-idf weight of a term is the product
  of its tf weight and its idf weight: tf-idf_{t,d} = tf_{t,d} × idf_t."
  "We can view each document as a vector with one real-valued component for each term. The
  cosine similarity between two documents is then: sim(d₁, d₂) = (d₁/|d₁|) · (d₂/|d₂|)."

  Justifies the cosine similarity formula used in VSM and normalizing document vectors by
  their length.

  Log-frequency TF Weighting (§6.4.1, p.127):
  "Log frequency weighting: the log frequency weight of term t in d is: wf_{t,d} = 1 +
  log(tf_{t,d}) if tf_{t,d} > 0, else 0."

  Justifies the math.log(1 + tf) formula used in vsm_search.py instead of raw TF, which
  prevents high-frequency terms from dominating scores.

  Smooth IDF (§6.2.2, p.118–119):
  "The idf of a rare term is high, whereas the idf of a frequent term is low... idf_t =
  log(N / df_t)."

  The smooth variant log((N+1)/(df+1)) + 1 prevents zero IDF for universal terms and avoids
   division by zero.

  ---
  6. BM25 (Okapi BM25)

  (§11.4.3, p.232–234):
  "The Okapi BM25 formula, which was developed as part of the Okapi system... is: RSV_d =
  Σ_{t∈q} log[N/df_t] · (k₁+1)tf_{td} / (k₁((1-b)+b·L_d/L_avg) + tf_{td})"
  "where L_d is the length of document d and L_avg is the average document length in the
  collection. The constants k₁ and b are free parameters. A typical k₁ value is 1.2–2.0 and
   b = 0.75."

  This is the exact formula implemented in bm25_search.py with K1=1.5, B=0.75. The textbook
   also explains:
  "The term-frequency component... saturates: as tf increases, the component approaches
  k₁+1 asymptotically... The b parameter controls the extent to which the document length
  normalizes the tf."

  ---
  7. Multi-Field Search Architecture

  Field-specific scoring supports the design of searching across title, author, and body
  with different weights in all three models. This mirrors the zone scoring concept
  extended to probabilistic and vector space scoring functions.

